Activity 3: Enhancing Accessible CSS

CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) is a powerful tool that allows web designers to customize the visual appearance and layout of web pages. CSS can also be used to enhance the accessibility of a website by adjusting various design elements to make them easier to read and use for people with disabilities.

The following are some specific ways in which CSS can be used to improve accessibility:

- Adjusting Color Contrast: Color contrast is an important consideration for web designers because low-contrast text can be difficult to read for people with visual impairments. CSS can be used to adjust the color contrast of text and background colors to make them easier to distinguish. For example, you can increase the contrast of text by adding a text-shadow or by adjusting the background color of the text container. You can also use tools like the WCAG Contrast Checker to ensure that your color contrast meets accessibility standards.

- Resizing Text: Text size is another important consideration for web designers because small text can be difficult to read for people with visual impairments or cognitive disabilities. CSS can be used to adjust the font size of text to make it more legible. For example, you can use the `font-size` property to increase the size of body text or headings. You can also use relative font sizes like `em` or `rem` to ensure that text scales proportionally with the user's browser settings.

- Improving Keyboard Navigation: Keyboard navigation is essential for users who cannot use a mouse, including those with motor impairments or visual impairments. CSS can be used to ensure that keyboard users can easily navigate through a website. For example, you can use the `:focus` pseudo-class to highlight the currently focused element, making it easier for keyboard users to keep track of their location on the page. You can also use the `tabindex` attribute to specify the order in which elements should be navigated with the keyboard.

Here's an example of how CSS can be used to improve accessibility:

```css
/* Increase text size */
body {
  font-size: 18px;
}

/* Improve color contrast */
h1, h2, h3, h4, h5, h6, p {
  text-shadow: 1px 1px 1px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.5);
  background-color: #ffffff;
}

/* Improve keyboard navigation */
a:focus, button:focus, input:focus {
  outline: 2px solid #4d90fe;
}
```

In this example, the `font-size` property is used to increase the size of body text to 18px, making it easier to read. The `text-shadow` property is used to add a subtle shadow to headings and paragraphs, making them stand out more against the background. The `background-color` property is set to white to ensure that text has high contrast against the background.

Finally, the `:focus` pseudo-class is used to highlight the currently focused element with a blue outline, making it easier for keyboard users to keep track of their location on the page. This is particularly important for users with visual impairments or motor impairments who rely on keyboard navigation.

